# Network Troubleshooting & Reconnaissance Commands

## Overview

Network troubleshooting and reconnaissance commands are essential tools for Network Engineers, System Administrators, SOC Analysts, and Cybersecurity Professionals. These commands help diagnose connectivity issues, gather network information, identify active hosts, inspect DNS records, monitor network interfaces, and troubleshoot communication problems.

Understanding these commands is crucial for both defensive and offensive security operations.

---

# 1. Ping

## Purpose
The `ping` command is used to test connectivity between your device and another host on a network.

It sends ICMP (Internet Control Message Protocol) Echo Request packets and waits for Echo Reply packets.

## Syntax

```bash
ping <IP_Address>
ping <Domain_Name>
```

## Example

```bash
ping 8.8.8.8
ping google.com
```

## What It Does

- Checks whether a host is reachable.
- Measures network latency.
- Verifies basic network connectivity.
- Helps identify packet loss.

## Use Cases

- Testing internet connectivity.
- Verifying server availability.
- Diagnosing network communication issues.

---

# 2. Netstat

## Purpose

`netstat` (Network Statistics) displays active network connections, listening ports, routing tables, and protocol statistics.

## Syntax

```bash
netstat
```

## Common Examples

```bash
netstat -ano
netstat -an
netstat -r
```

## What It Shows

- Active TCP connections
- Active UDP connections
- Listening ports
- Routing information
- Interface statistics

## Use Cases

- Identifying open ports.
- Monitoring active connections.
- Detecting suspicious network activity.
- Troubleshooting network issues.

---

# 3. Tracert / Traceroute

## Purpose

`tracert` (Windows) or `traceroute` (Linux) displays the path packets take from your system to the destination host.

## Syntax

### Windows

```cmd
tracert google.com
```

### Linux

```bash
traceroute google.com
```

## What It Does

- Displays every router (hop) between source and destination.
- Measures latency at each hop.
- Helps locate where network delays occur.

## Use Cases

- Diagnosing routing issues.
- Finding network bottlenecks.
- Identifying packet drop locations.

---

# 4. PathPing

## Purpose

`pathping` combines the functionality of Ping and Tracert.

## Syntax

```cmd
pathping google.com
```

## What It Does

- Traces the route.
- Calculates packet loss at each hop.
- Provides detailed network performance information.

## Benefits

- More detailed than ping.
- More analytical than tracert.
- Useful for identifying unstable network paths.

---

# 5. Route

## Purpose

The `route` command displays and manages routing tables.

## Syntax

```bash
route print
```

or

```bash
route
```

## What It Does

- Displays routing information.
- Shows how packets are forwarded.
- Helps troubleshoot routing problems.

## Common Uses

- Viewing routes.
- Adding routes.
- Deleting routes.
- Modifying network paths.

---

# 6. NSLookup

## Purpose

`nslookup` is used to query DNS servers and obtain domain-related information.

## Syntax

```bash
nslookup google.com
```

## What It Returns

- Domain IP address
- DNS records
- DNS server information

## Use Cases

- DNS troubleshooting.
- Verifying DNS records.
- Investigating domain mappings.

## Why It Matters

DNS translates domain names into IP addresses so systems can communicate over networks.

---

# 7. Telnet

## Purpose

`telnet` is commonly used to test connectivity to a specific port on a remote host.

## Syntax

```bash
telnet google.com 80
```

## What It Does

- Attempts a TCP connection.
- Checks whether a service is reachable.
- Tests application-layer connectivity.

## Common Ports Tested

| Service | Port |
|----------|--------|
| HTTP | 80 |
| HTTPS | 443 |
| SMTP | 25 |
| FTP | 21 |

## Use Cases

- Testing web servers.
- Verifying open ports.
- Troubleshooting service availability.

---

# 8. Hostname

## Purpose

Displays the name of the current system.

## Syntax

```bash
hostname
```

## What It Does

Returns the computer or device hostname configured on the operating system.

## Example Output

```bash
DESKTOP-ABC123
```

## Use Cases

- Device identification.
- Asset management.
- Network inventory.

